      <div class="finding-card">
        <h3>Time Decay Accelerates in the Final 30 Days</h3>
        <p>Options lose roughly one-third of their time value in the last 30 days before expiration. This "theta decay curve" makes buying short-dated options expensive and selling them profitable. If you're buying options, consider 45–60 DTE to minimize theta drag. If selling, the 30–45 DTE sweet spot maximizes daily decay while limiting gamma risk from sudden moves.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="finding-card">
        <h3>Implied Volatility Is the Hidden Cost of Options</h3>
        <p>Two options with the same strike and expiration can have wildly different premiums depending on IV. Before earnings, IV can spike 50–100%, inflating premiums. After the announcement, IV crushes back to normal — often causing losses even if you predicted the direction correctly. Always check IV percentile before entering a trade: buy when IV is low (below 30th percentile) and sell when IV is high (above 70th percentile).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="finding-card">
        <h3>Defined-Risk Spreads Outperform Naked Options for Most Traders</h3>
        <p>Vertical spreads (bull call, bear put) cap both your max loss and max profit. While they reduce potential upside, they dramatically improve capital efficiency and risk management. A bull call spread might cost $2.00 with a max profit of $3.00 — a 150% return if the stock moves above the short strike. The equivalent naked call might need a $5+ move for the same return, with higher theta and vega exposure.</p>
