});

// ===== FAQ =====
var faqs = [
  {q:"How do you calculate options profit?",a:"Options profit depends on whether you bought or sold the contract. For a long call: profit = (underlying price − strike price − premium paid) × 100 × contracts. For a long put: profit = (strike price − underlying price − premium paid) × 100 × contracts. The premium you paid is your maximum loss when buying options."},
  {q:"What is breakeven price for an option?",a:"Breakeven is the underlying stock price at which your option position neither makes nor loses money at expiration. For a long call: breakeven = strike price + premium paid. For a long put: breakeven = strike price − premium paid. Multi-leg strategies like spreads and iron condors have multiple breakeven points."},
  {q:"What are the Options Greeks?",a:"The Greeks measure how an option's price changes in response to market factors. Delta (Δ) measures price sensitivity to a $1 move in the underlying — calls range 0 to 1, puts −1 to 0. Gamma (Γ) measures how fast delta changes. Theta (Θ) measures time decay per day. Vega (ν) measures sensitivity to a 1% change in implied volatility."},
  {q:"What is a covered call strategy?",a:"A covered call involves owning 100 shares of a stock and selling a call option against them. Your max profit is capped at the strike price minus your stock purchase price, plus the premium received. It's a conservative income strategy: you collect premium in exchange for capping your upside. Best when neutral-to-slightly-bullish."},
  {q:"What is an iron condor?",a:"An iron condor is a four-leg neutral strategy that profits when the underlying stays within a range. You sell an out-of-the-money put and call, then buy a further OTM put and call for protection. Max profit is the total premium received. Max loss is the width of the wider spread minus premium received. Best in low-volatility environments."},
  {q:"How does time decay (theta) affect options?",a:"Theta measures daily time decay — the amount an option loses in value each day. Options lose value as expiration approaches because there's less time for a favorable move. Decay accelerates in the final 30 days. Theta is negative for buyers (hurts you) and positive for sellers (helps you). At-the-money options have the highest theta."},
  {q:"What is the difference between buying and selling options?",a:"Buying options gives you the right but not obligation to buy (calls) or sell (puts) at the strike price. Max loss is the premium paid. Selling options obligates you to fulfill the contract if assigned. Sellers collect premium upfront but face potentially unlimited loss on naked calls. Roughly 60–80% of options expire worthless, statistically favoring sellers."},
  {q:"How accurate is an options profit calculator?",a:"An options profit calculator is highly accurate for profit/loss at expiration. Real-world results may differ due to bid-ask spreads, early assignment risk, IV changes, dividends, and commissions. The Greeks displayed here are simplified Black-Scholes estimates — for precise Greeks, use your broker's platform which incorporates real-time volatility surfaces."}
];

